'Let me run ahead,&rsquo; said Charlotte, &lsquo;and see if I can guess what you are aiming at. Just as everything has an attraction to itself, so too there must be a relationship with other things.&lsquo;
&ndash;Goethe, Elective Affinities
 &lsquo;Elective affinity,&rsquo; a concept in part popularized by Goethe&rsquo;s 1809 classic novel, attempts to describe a sociological and political economic imperative. In his seminal work, The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism, Max Weber appropriates the term to outline a kind of reciprocal causality&ndash;the way that the &lsquo;spirit&rsquo; of a political economy shapes and is in turn shaped by the cohesion and adherence of its relationship to its form.
